<p>in the BMW ‘i’ model line up, there’s only the i3 and this i8. the i3 looks similar with the i3, and it goes the same too with the construction process. the car structure is made out of CFRP, that stands for Carbon Fiber Reinforced Plastic. It’s the same material you would find in Airbus A350 XWB and lamborghini sesto element. Aluminum becomes out of date these days. its easy to recognize the material,a dark rubber like structure with thin white lines visible at the door seals. 
</p>

<p>its basically a feel a bit of gymnastic to climb in out of the car. its partly because the i8 is so lowered to the ground, but its also because of the white tall sill at the bottom and open door at the top. you kinda have to put one leg in, sit on the sill and scooch over and pull the other leg in if you wanna drop into your fancy ride without looking like a fool. on the way out, you have to remember to reverse the process or otherwise you’ll end up with the hand on the pavements when flopping out of the car. rear passenger seat is quite small, you can fit in a child or two, and that’s it. 

entering the cockpit the thin blue colored seatbelt will catch your attention first. I mean like come on, it’s a future generation car, I’m sure they wanna change everything, till the last possible bit. the central cluster and drive selector looks very much the same with the i3. but instead of its drive selector which is located at the paddle shifter, for i8 it is properly located at the center. compared to its little brother i3, the i8’s interior looks more like a proper sports car, but with a blend of future tech. apart from this, it’s also equipped with navi screen which serves a BMW iConnectedDrive. everything from the weather,news ,making calls and car’s health right in front of the screen. plus there’s an app to monitor the car too. Now that’s something you won’t find in a typical Hybrid.</p>

<h3>Performance</h3>
<p>Its quite rare to find a MR (middle-engine-rear-drive) vehicle these day. the i8 engine twin power turbo 1.5 liter 3 cylinder engine with 231 hp peak performance combined with 131 hp worth of electric motor. that should enough to propel the car in 0-60 test for about  4 seconds. its definitely not the fastest car they ever produced, but it’s pretty awesome considering how small the engine is, combined with its electric drive system. Oh, and not to forget regenerative braking system which had become pretty common in hybrid car nowadays. there are 3 available driving mode; COMFORT, ECO PRO and SPORT. the comfort mode lets you drive all electric while sport mode unleash the soaring sound of the engine. the engine sound is channeled directly to the passenger compartment for a better driving experience, more like lexus LFA which has the yamaha guys tuned the engine sound for them.</p>
<p>

	<h3>Verdict</h3>
Yes, the i8 is the most outrageous design I’ve ever seen, and that should create a high demand for it. But no matter how good a car is, it would be useless at the end of a test drive if you have the right amount of money. And for this one, it starts at ..(drumroll)RM 470,000 and upwards. Even if you have the money, it’s definitely worth to wait a while for charging facilities to become available in your town before buying one.</p>

